Plan, Christian Romeo

Microloans are a lifeline for many Filipinos, providing essential capital to those traditionally underserved by banks. As digital platforms transform microlending with easier access to personal loans, the key to longevity lies in building a robust customer base despite the pressures of rising interest rates and diminishing profits.


During my two-year tenure as Risk Analytics Manager for Lending at Mynt, I've been intimately involved in assessing the potential risks of business decisions, with a particular focus on customer reactions. We heavily rely on customer reviews and feedback as measurable indicators of our performance. These insights are not just metrics, they are foundational to the innovations and enhancements of our products and services.



What are the factors influencing user satisfaction?


Data Science Solution

With the rapid influx of customer feedback, these insights can become overwhelming and seem like mere noise if left untapped. However, when leveraged effectively, they become invaluable. Utilizing Machine Learning to perform Sentiment Analysis allows us to discern customer preferences and pinpoint their primary concerns. Harnessing this technology can guide our business strategy, steering our efforts in a direction that aligns with our customers' needs and experiences, thus fostering a more holistic approach to growth and improvement.

Scope

The scope of my project will cover the use of text data to predict the rating and provide the key words and statements that drive this rating.

It will focus on the available lending services in the Philippines and which to select.

Value Creation

If we have all these reviews and we're able to maximize their use, we'll be able to understand their feedbacks on a much deeper level and we can act on it through incorporating these insights to our Product Development Strategies. We can go as far as offering personalized responses as well as robust chatbots which will eventually lead to customer retention

Implication to me as a Data Scientist

The most obvious answer is growth but this is a huge step towards building the projects I'm genuinely interested in as I value the sentiments of my customers.


Methodology

Table 1. Methology Overview are the steps I have taken to address the problem statement.
Step
Process
Description
1 Data Extraction and Cleaning Upload the file and select the relevant columns and limit to just the lending app reviews. We will remove the stopwords at the start.
2 Exploratory Data Analysis Perform EDA to gain understanding on the data and its characteristics, and identify any trends.
3 Data Vectorization Represent text as vectors through bag-of-words representation with TF-IDF
3 Dimensionality Reductions Reduce these vectorized data into the optimal number of Latent Factors
4 Model-building Include baselines so we could compare the performance of our models. Select the best models and best parameters that will offer the most interpretable and most accurate results
5 Results Utilize Precision, Recall, and Precision to determine accuracy of model
6 Insights and Recommendation Summarize the insights from the generated results, and provide recommendations given the insights acquired


Data Description


Data Scope & Limitations

1. Lending Apps Only
The data covers all fintech apps including MAYA, BPI, BDO, METROBANK, ETC. which offer multiple services like bank transfers, savings accounts, and investments. This will project will be limited to the apps that offer personal loans only.

This is due to the growing competitive space in lending as GCash has already reached Php50B and it has introduced varying lending services which proves the popularity of these services.

2. 15% of total dataset only
This is due to the dataset consisting of more than 1M rows which we logically limited to just 80K.

# 1. Load data with specified datatypes and columns.
columns = ['review_text', 'review_rating', 'application_id']
dtypes = {'review_text': 'string', 'review_rating': 'int8', 'application_id': 'string'}
df = pd.read_csv('phbanks_app_reviews.csv', usecols=columns, dtype=dtypes).dropna()


# 2. Filter out non-lending specific financial service apps.
not_just_lending_apps = ['com.fronde.mbanking.android.pckg.bpi', 'com.citibank.CitibankPH', 'com.rcbc.mobilebanking', 'www.mobile.bdo.com.ph', 
                         'com.landbank.mobilebanking','com.paymaya',  'com.unionbankph.online', 'com.tonik.mobile', 'com.securitybank.online',
                         'ph.com.bdo.retail', 'ph.seabank.seabank', 'com.cimbph.app2022', 'ph.uniondigital.superapp', 'ph.com.gotyme',
                         'com.iexceed.unoConsumerBanking', 'ph.com.metrobank.mcc.mbonline', 'com.bpi.ng.app'
                        ]
df = df[~df['application_id'].isin(not_just_lending_apps)]


# 3. Normalize review text.
def normalize_text(text): return re.sub(r'[^a-z0-9\s]', '', text.lower())
df['review_text'] = df['review_text'].apply(normalize_text).str.strip()

# Drop rows with empty review_text
lending_df['review_text'] = lending_df['review_text'].str.strip()


# 4. Remove stop words.
stop_words = stopwords.words('english') + ['ng', 'nang', 'ang', 'yung', 'yun', 'ung', 'po', 'na', 'sa', 'app', 'good', 'loan', 'tala', 'apps', 'ok', 'ko']
df['review_text'] = df['review_text'].apply(lambda x: ' '.join([word for word in word_tokenize(x) if word.lower() not in stop_words]))


# 5. Assign sentiment labels and remove empty reviews.
df['sentiment'] = df['review_rating'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x <= 3 else 1)
df = df[df['review_text'] != '']


# 6. Save the cleaned DataFrame.
pickle_filename = "lending_df.pkl"
df.to_pickle(pickle_filename)

# Placeholder data for positive and negative words, this will be replaced with actual data from filtered_sdf

negative_word_freq = Counter(negative_words)

Data Vectorization:
Term Frequency-Inverse Document Frequency (TFIDF)


TFIDF in loan app reviews clarifies positive (fast, easy) vs. negative (scammed, rejected) sentiments.

Dimensionality Reduction:
Singlular Value Decomposition (SVD)

We opted for 400 n_components to explain 80% of the variance which I am personally comfortable with already

lending_df = pd.read_pickle("lending_df.pkl")

print("Population per class:{}".format(df_state))
print("Proportion Chance Criterion: {:0.2f}%".format(100*num.sum()))
print("1.25 * Proportion Chance Criterion: {:0.2f}%".format(1.25*100*num.sum()))

from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.feature_extraction.text import TfidfVectorizer
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.decomposition import TruncatedSVD
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report

logreg_pipe = Pipeline([
    ('tfidf', TfidfVectorizer(max_features=3000, stop_words=final_stopwords)),
    ('svd', TruncatedSVD(n_components=350)),
    ('logreg', LogisticRegression(random_state=42, C=100, class_weight='balanced'))
], verbose=True)

# 1. Access the SVD component and its singular values from the pipeline
svd = logreg_pipe.named_steps['svd']
singular_values = svd.singular_values_

# 2. Create a DataFrame to display SVD components and their singular values
svd_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Component': range(1, len(singular_values) + 1),
    'Singular_Value': singular_values
})

# 3. Access the logistic regression model and its coefficients
logreg_model = logreg_pipe.named_steps['logreg']
flattened_coefficients = logreg_model.coef_.flatten()

# 4. Append the logistic regression coefficients to the SVD DataFrame
svd_df['LogReg_Coefficient'] = flattened_coefficients

Top Latent Factors for the Positive Sentiments


The words surfacing in the SVD components for the personal loan web app reviews reveal a complex sentiment landscape. For instance, Component 184 mixes high praise with serious grievances, suggesting that while some users are delighted, others face notable frustrations. Component 280's juxtaposition of "considerate" with "slow" and "failed" reflects a dichotomy in service quality perception, where commendable personal interactions are marred by operational inefficiencies. Meanwhile, Component 189 shows gratitude for assistance received but is shadowed by mentions of "problem" and "ill," indicating that positive experiences are not without their challenges.

The mixture of positive and negative language within these supposed positive components points to a potential misalignment in the model's sentiment discrimination. It underscores the need for a refined SVD approach, perhaps through adjusting the number of components to capture sentiment more distinctly or by employing more nuanced preprocessing strategies. Such improvements could lead to a clearer differentiation in sentiment analysis, ensuring that positive and negative feedback are more accurately represented in their respective components.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Setup the plot - 3 subplots side by side
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))

# Iterate through each of the top 3 components
for i in [2,1,0]:
    component_num = top_3.iloc[i, 0]  # Assuming top_3 is a DataFrame
    selected_component = svd.components_[component_num]

    tfidf_vectorizer = logreg_pipe.named_steps['tfidf']
    feature_names = tfidf_vectorizer.get_feature_names_out()

    # Map each weight to its corresponding word
    word_weights = dict(zip(feature_names, selected_component))

    # Sort the words by their weights
    sorted_words = sorted(word_weights.items(), key=lambda x: x[1], reverse=True)

    # Number of top features to visualize
    top_n = 20

    # Split the words and their weights
    top_words, top_weights = zip(*sorted_words[:top_n])

    # Create bar plot on the ith subplot
    axes[i].barh(top_words, top_weights)
    axes[i].set_xlabel('Weight')
    axes[i].set_title(f'Top {top_n} Words in SVD Component {component_num}')
    axes[i].invert_yaxis()  # To display the highest value at the top

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Conclusion & Recommendation


In conclusion, the use of TFIDF in conjunction with Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) and Logistic Regression has proven to be a robust approach for sentiment analysis within the context of personal loan web app reviews. TFIDF effectively highlighted key terms that were crucial for distinguishing between positive and negative sentiments, while SVD helped to reduce the dimensionality of the feature space, enhancing the Logistic Regression model's ability to detect nuanced sentiment patterns.

The results yielded an F1 score of 85%, surpassing the benchmark of 1.25 times the Performance Comparison Criterion (PCC), which stood at 79%. This demonstrates a tangible improvement in the model's predictive capability. The higher F1 score indicates that the model not only accurately identifies positive sentiments but also maintains a balanced precision and recall, a critical aspect when dealing with imbalanced datasets.

From a business perspective, the implementation of a machine learning pipeline encapsulating TFIDF, SVD, and Logistic Regression contributes to scalability and automation. This advancement in sentiment analysis allows companies to process vast amounts of textual feedback efficiently, which is pivotal for understanding customer sentiments at scale. By leveraging these insights, businesses can pinpoint specific areas of their service that require enhancement, ultimately driving usage and customer satisfaction. The slight edge in performance, as indicated by the F1 score, also suggests that companies can rely on this model to inform strategic decisions, leading to targeted improvements and more effective resource allocation.


To finetune your sentiment analysis, tweak the TFIDF vectorizer by adjusting features and trialing n-grams to catch nuanced language patterns in customer feedback. Experiment with the number of dimensions in SVD for capturing variance more effectively and apply tools like topic modeling to interpret the decomposed components better.

In optimizing the Logistic Regression model, a thorough grid search could refine crucial parameters, potentially enhancing model precision. Also, consider incorporating ensemble techniques like Random Forests or Gradient Boosting, which may be more adept at handling the complexities of sentiment data. Alongside the F1 score, the ROC-AUC score could offer deeper insights into your model's performance across various thresholds.

Address class imbalance in your dataset head-on by employing techniques such as SMOTE, which can significantly improve model robustness by providing a more balanced training set. Post-modeling, tools like LIME or SHAP could shed light on your model's decision-making process, ensuring that the results remain transparent and interpretable. Maintain the model's sharpness by continuously benchmarking against fresh data, adapting to the latest linguistic and sentiment shifts.
